\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This report often uses variable names
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nomenclature!equations
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in equations, and sometimes there is potential for confusion because the
 variable names consist of multiple characters.
 In most cases, to denote that the variable name is the variable in the
 equation (as opposed to each of the letters in the variable name representing
 quantities to be multiplied together), the variable name has been enclosed
 in brackets, as in {TASX}.
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
variable!names in brackets
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In addition, variable names are displayed with upright Roman character
 sets, while other symbols in equations are shown using slanted (script)
 character sets as is conventional for mathematical equations.
 In cases where code
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nomenclature!code
\end_layout

\end_inset

 segments (usually expressed in C code) are included to document how calculation
s are performed, typewriter character sets indicate that the segment is
 a representation of how the processing could be coded.
 Such a code segment is not always a direct copy of the code in use, but
 such code is sometimes the most convenient way to express the algorithm
 in use.
\end_layout

